It would seem there is at least a majority of the population thinks this should be against the law. This is something that I consider to be "Low Hanging Fruit". My website will include a "Low Hanging Fruit" board where the highest priority issues are shared and unofficially voted on.

It would work like this:
<ol>
  <li>Display a list of issues where there is general agreement that changes are needed.</li>
  <li>From the list of issues, the user can click a link that will show proposed solutions. The user can then rate that proposed solution on a scale of 1-10. 1 meaning they do not like the idea at all. 10 means they love the idea and think action should be taken.</li>
  <li>From the list of proposed solutions, you can also click on a link to see which politicians are championing specific causes.</li>
</ol>


The list from #2 above is where the politicians get involved. I want them focusing on those issues, so that we can pass laws that address the wants and needs of the people that are most obvious.
<br><br>
My thought process is to go after the low hanging fruit topics as early as possible in my presidency so that by the time the first annual vote comes around we can solve some of those issues. Then, come January 1st of the next year, we can create a new list and get to work on those issues for the following year.
<br><br>
This brings me to the next page on the website, the "Current Events" board. The idea here is to share ideas on things that xxx. This board will be similar to the Low Hanging Fruit board, but it will be refreshed on the first of each month. I may find a way to archive the proposed solutions and votes on those solutions, but my demo for now just clears out and starts over on the first of each month.
<br><br>
Finally, I will include a 'State Issues' board. This will show some of the biggest concerns at the state level. It will also allow for user to rate the solutions that they most agree on. Ideally, the state votes would be limited to a persons home state... but for now my demo just keeps to one vote per IP address, regardless of which state they live in.
<br><br>
So, one year from now, I expect to have a whole bunch of low hanging fruit ready to be decided on by you, the people.
<br><br>
After one year, I expect that low hanging fruit board to be much smaller.
<br><br>
So, let's move on to the big board. The big board will have a lot more topics. These will primarily be topics where a majority of people lean a certain way, but fixes are not being implemented.
<br><br>
I would ultimately like to require a login that is tied to social security, or other citizen approved identification. This way, we could get a very accurate read on what the citizens want.
<br><br>
If the AI companies want to be on our platform, they must agree to sharing their code to a select few government employees who will oversee AI as a whole. My team will use AI to verify AI is on the up and up. No political bias, just base it on what the people are saying. Obviously, we are going to need to firewall this from both foreign users as well as all kinds of bots. And really, if people are brazen enought to try and hack the government website, hopefully our people are smart enough to track them down.
<br><br>
One of the most important issues of the day is healthcare. I think it is pretty obvious that this is an industry that is ripe for fraud. By requiring any healthcare provider to submit their charges we should be able to use AI to root out those that are taking advantage of the system. Now, this is really important, the main idea is not to punish them
<br><br>
