<br><br>
For now, I am going to just utilize ChatGPT for answering our questions. In the future, I will add a few more AI sites and build in a comparison tool to verify just how "in agreement" they are. It will be a fun exercise to compare and contrast which each AI company spits out.
<br><br>
One of the things I don't get is why are they not using AI to track down the scams that pop-up. I was almost scammed by a pretty sophisticated setup where they sent what looked like official email that said call this number for discounts on your policy. I call up that number, and somebody answers like the are repping the companies. They had me all the way up to telling me I needed to go buy gift cards and use those as payment. That's when I said sure, I will go do that. A short google search later told me this was widespread. If I can google it, the government should surely be able to use AI to shut that industry down.... or at least bring it to it's knees.
<br><br>
For the most part, I will let ChatGPT do the talking. However, I will make once exception and that is corporate financing of elections. We have to stop letting them run our lives, and start making them accountable to our needs. Imagine if that instead of spending billions of dollars a year bribing the politicians, they could give that back to the communities.
<br><br>
My system relies on taking that part out.

Let's talk about gerrymandering a little bit. In my mind, gerrymandering is basically the people in power trying to cheat the vote. Isn't that something we should be against as a population?

I would propose we settle the matter once and for all. Use statistics based analisys, to create maps that all states must ahdere to. I am not entirely sure, but maybe something like breaking up each state into 10 population areas. It gets complicated when you bring urban vs. rural into the picture, but here is what I asked ChatGPT as a starting point:

